Training Models to predict London House Prices

Khushi Jaiswal

2025-01-06

1 Introduction and learning objectives

The purpose of this project is to build an estimation engine to guide investment decisions in London house market.

I will first build machine learning algorithms (and tune them) to estimate the house prices given variety of information about each property. Then, using my algorithm, I will choose 200 houses to invest in out of about 2000 houses on the market at the moment.

Learning objectives

  1. Using different data mining algorithms for prediction.
  2. Dealing with large data sets
  3. Tuning data mining algorithms
  4. Interpreting data mining algorithms and deducing importance of variables
  5. Using results of data mining algorithms to make business decisions

2 Load data

There are two sets of data, i) training data that has the actual prices ii) out of sample data that has the asking prices. I will first Load both data sets.

3.2 Useful Vis 2 - Correlation of Numerical Variables

This correlation matrix is only of the numerical variables that we have in the data set. Even though the colours are already showing the level of correlations between the variables, the sizes of the circles make the comparison easier. We can see that the total floor area has a strong positive correlation with all the other variables (expect energy consumption). On the other hand, a strong negative correlation can be seen between number of rooms and energy consumption and also between the price and current energy consumption. The variables which show a strong correlation (negative or positive) will be most useful to us.

library(corrplot)

# produce a correlation table using GGally::ggcor()
# this takes a while to plot

library("GGally")
london_house_prices_2019_training %>% 
  select(-ID) %>% #keep Y variable last
  ggcorr(method = c("pairwise", "pearson"), layout.exp = 2,label_round=2, label = TRUE,label_size = 2,hjust = 1,nbreaks = 5,size = 2,angle = -20)

Observations from the Correlations table: First off, we can see that there are no 2 variables that have a strong weak correlation. There are a lot more negative correlations than there are positive ones. Most of the interactions fall in the -0.2 to 0.2 correlations coefficient range. There are fewer variables with a strong positive correlation obvious examples including number of rooms & floor area and the current & potential CO2 emissions. There are fewer still variables that have weak interaction. We are mainly interested in the price of the properties. The variables that most impact the prices of houses are average income, zone, current & potential co2 emission levels, floor area and the number of rooms. We should definitely consider these factors when trying to predict the prices. Other variables that have weak correlation levels with price are less important to us because they do not have a large enough impact on the price to be used to predict it.

4 Training ML models

Now that we have properly understood the variables in our data set as well as which ones have greater impact on the price and which less, we will be able to use them to train our models.

### ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ BEST MODEL ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ ###

#Define control variables
control <- trainControl (
    method="cv",
    number=5,
    savePredictions = 'all',
    verboseIter=FALSE)
# ADDING INTERACTION VARIABLES
model1_lm <- train(
    price ~ water_company +
           property_type +
           freehold_or_leasehold +
           latitude +
           longitude +
           total_floor_area +
           co2_emissions_current +
           average_income +
           london_zone +
           num_tube_lines +
           windows_energy_eff +
           altitude +
           distance_to_station:london_zone +
           property_type:total_floor_area +
           distance_to_station +
           number_habitable_rooms +
           number_habitable_rooms:total_floor_area +
           average_income:london_zone +
           windows_energy_eff:energy_consumption_current +
           freehold_or_leasehold:average_income +
           district,
    train_data,
    method = "lm",
    trControl = control,
    preProcess = c("center", "scale")
)
# Summary of the results
# summary(model1_lm)

### ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ testData ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ ###

predictions <- predict(model1_lm, newdata = test_data) # Generate predictions
actuals <- test_data$price # Compare predictions with actual values

# evaluation metrics
library(Metrics)
##

r2_value <- cor(actuals, predictions)^2

The more the importance, the more the variables helps in prediction, hence the better it would be to use it to train our model.

# we can check variable importance as well

4.1.2 Predict the values in testing and out of sample data

Below I use the predict function to test the performance of the model in testing data and summarize the performance of the linear regression model.

# We can predict the testing values

predictions <- predict(model1_lm,test_data)

lr_results<-data.frame(  RMSE = RMSE(predictions, test_data$price), 
                            Rsquare = R2(predictions, test_data$price))
                            
lr_results                         
##     RMSE   Rsquare
## 1 290107 0.6741513
#We can predict prices for out of sample data the same way
predictions_oos <- predict(model1_lm,london_house_prices_2019_out_of_sample)
# print(predictions_oos)




## out of sample results

# Extract actual and predicted values
actuals <- london_house_prices_2019_out_of_sample$asking_price  # Replace `price` with the actual response variable name
lr_predictions_oos <- predict(model1_lm, london_house_prices_2019_out_of_sample)
# Calculate RMSE
rmse <- sqrt(mean((lr_predictions_oos - actuals)^2))
# Calculate R-squared
rss <- sum((lr_predictions_oos - actuals)^2)  # Residual sum of squares
tss <- sum((actuals - mean(actuals))^2)    # Total sum of squares
r_squared <- 1 - (rss / tss)
# Print results
cat("Linear regression RMSE:", rmse, "\n")
## Linear regression RMSE: 404307.8
cat("Linear regression R-squared:", r_squared, "\n")
## Linear regression R-squared: 0.6430721

4.3 KNN Model

KNN can be used for both classification and regression - so I will be using it here.

### ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ BEST MODEL ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ ###

# tuning parameters
tune_grid <- expand.grid(k = 5)
control <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                        number = 10, 
                        savePredictions = 'all', 
                        verboseIter = FALSE)
# Model 3: Training a KNN model with selected features and interaction terms
model3_knn <- train(
    price ~ water_company + 
           property_type + 
           freehold_or_leasehold + 
           latitude + 
           longitude + 
           total_floor_area + 
           co2_emissions_current + 
           average_income + 
           london_zone + 
           num_tube_lines + 
           windows_energy_eff + 
           altitude + 
           distance_to_station:london_zone + 
           property_type:total_floor_area + 
           distance_to_station + 
           number_habitable_rooms + 
           number_habitable_rooms:total_floor_area + 
           average_income:london_zone + 
           windows_energy_eff:energy_consumption_current + 
           freehold_or_leasehold:average_income + 
           district,
    data = train_data, 
    method = "knn",
    trControl = control,  # Use 10-fold cross-validation
    tuneGrid = tune_grid,  # Number of parameter values train function will try
    preProcess = c("center", "scale")  # Center and scale the data (important for KNN)
)


### ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ testData ~~~~ ~~~~ ~~~~ ###

predictions <- predict(model3_knn, newdata = test_data) # Generate predictions
actuals <- test_data$price # Compare predictions with actual values

# evaluation metrics

5 Stacking

Now that I have traine 4 models that are giving me satisfactory RMSE’s and RSquared’s, I will be using stacking to ensemble them on top of each other to create a model that will be combining each of the 4 models to produce the best predictions.

library(caret)
library(caretEnsemble)
library(ggplot2)
library(pROC)

# removing NA values 
# train_data_new <- na.omit(train_data)




# Train Control with RMSE and R-squared as metrics
my_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",                # Cross-validation
  number = 5,                   # 5 folds
  savePredictions = "final",    # Save final predictions
  verboseIter = FALSE,           # Show iterations
  summaryFunction = defaultSummary # Use RMSE and R-squared
)

# Train the models and stack them
model_list <- caretList(
  price ~ water_company + 
           property_type + 
           freehold_or_leasehold + 
           latitude + 
           longitude + 
           total_floor_area + 
           co2_emissions_current + 
           average_income + 
           london_zone + 
           num_tube_lines + 
           windows_energy_eff + 
           altitude + 
           distance_to_station:london_zone + 
           property_type:total_floor_area + 
           distance_to_station + 
           number_habitable_rooms + 
           number_habitable_rooms:total_floor_area + 
           average_income:london_zone + 
           windows_energy_eff:energy_consumption_current + 
           freehold_or_leasehold:average_income + 
           district, 
  data = train_data,             # Your training dataset
  trControl = my_control,        # Train control
  methodList = c("lm"),          # Logistic regression for baseline
  tuneList = list(
    tree = caretModelSpec(method = "rpart", tuneLength = 10),
    knn = caretModelSpec(method = "knn", tuneGrid = expand.grid(k = 5)),
    rf = caretModelSpec(
      method = "ranger",
      tuneGrid = expand.grid(mtry = 39, splitrule = "extratrees", min.node.size = 1)
    )
  )
)
## Growing trees.. Progress: 58%. Estimated remaining time: 22 seconds.
## Growing trees.. Progress: 83%. Estimated remaining time: 6 seconds.
## Growing trees.. Progress: 82%. Estimated remaining time: 6 seconds.
## Growing trees.. Progress: 60%. Estimated remaining time: 20 seconds.
# Stacking the models
stacked_model <- caretStack(
  model_list,
  method = "lm", # Use LM to combine models
  metric = "RMSE", # Use RMSE as the performance metric
  trControl = my_control
)

cat("STACKED MODEL")

6 Pick investments

In this section I will use my best algorithm to choose 200 properties from the 2000 properties in the out of sample data.

library(dplyr)

outOfSampleData <- london_house_prices_2019_out_of_sample
predicted_values <- predict(stacked_model, newdata = outOfSampleData)

# If predict() returns a list, convert it to a numeric vector
if (is.list(predicted_values)) {
  predicted_values <- unlist(predicted_values) # Flatten the list into a numeric vector
}

# Add predicted_price column to the data frame
outOfSampleData <- outOfSampleData %>%
  mutate(predicted_price = as.numeric(predicted_values)) # Ensure predictions are numeric

# Calculate investment potential and create the 'buy' column
outOfSampleData <- outOfSampleData %>%
  mutate(investment_potential = predicted_price - asking_price) %>% # Investment potential = predicted price - asking price
  arrange(desc(investment_potential)) %>% # Best investments on top
  mutate(buy = if_else(row_number() <= 200, 1, 0)) # Mark top 200 investments

# Inspect the resulting data frame
# head(outOfSampleData)

# Write the results to a CSV file
write.csv(outOfSampleData, "Jaiswal_Khushi.csv", row.names = FALSE)
